It is great there is more awareness of the issues with PFAs. But as a microbial bioremediation researcher I have to share that these "forever chemicals" ARE able to be broken down by reductive deflouronation, this is emerging research but there are many people working actively on solutions that are showing good results.
such as: https://pubs.acs.org/doi/abs/10.1021/acs.est.9b04047
and this is a general review: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0301479717307934

Thank you so much Trevor for shining a light on this very important issue! If anyone wants to know if their county's drinking water is contaminated with these chemicals, check this interactive map: http://static.ewg.org/reports/2015/pfoa_drinking_water/interactive_map/index.html Oh and if you're curious, go on google maps and see if you can spot dupont, chemours, or 3M in a contaminated county! (if you can't find it they might've just moved from the area- I've seen that)


Dupont has been poisoning people's drinking water for a long while now, parkersburg, west virginia is a clear example of that: https://highline.huffingtonpost.com/articles/en/welcome-to-beautiful-parkersburg/ It's good to finally see some awareness about a toxic manmade chemical that did not exist less than a century ago now being in about 97% of American's blood.
